0.body: This website contains all of the projects for SER120. Check Blackboard and the syllabus if you have questions about which projects are required and how they affect your grade.
0.title: Projects Overview

1.body: Using the wheels library, create a scene involving several objects. The scene can be whatever you want as long as it's appropriate for a classroom setting. The wheels library provides several classes to display simple shapes. You can use these to construct all of the objects in your scene. You can see a list of these shape classes in the wheels documentation on Blackboard.
1.breadcrumbs: Project 1: Wheels Scene » Project 1: Wheels Scene
1.title: Project 1: Wheels Scene

10.body: Using the wheels library, create a program with interactive elements. This can be a scene like in the previous project, or something completely different. Add interaction to wheels objects by extending wheels shapes (such as Rectangle and Ellipse) and overriding one or more of the mouse methods (such as mousePressed, mouseReleased, mouseClicked, or mouseDragged).

10.title: Project 2: Interactive Scene

14.body: Design at least two interactive elements to include in your program. You can add some UI elements to the scene from your previous project, allow direct interaction with objects in the scene, or do something else entirely. To give a few examples: A button that triggers some action when clicked A slider that gradually adjusts some property of an object A composite object that can be dragged around the screen An object that responds differently depending on where it is clicked In a separate document, answer the following questions about your design. This is your design writeup , and it must be submitted with the project. Describe your two interactive elements and how interacting with them affects the program. For an object to count, it must meet the following requirements: The interaction involves mouse input The object is visible The interaction is not limited to a single wheels shape (for example, an ellipse that can be dragged around on its own is too simple to count) The interaction causes a visible change in one or more objects Each interaction must involve a different type of change (for example, moving, resizing, or changing an object's color) Finally, note that I expect you to design your own objects and write these descriptions yourself. You objects should not be based on a classmate's objects, and you are not allowed to use ChatGPT or another LLM to assist with this writeup.
14.title: Task 1: Design

15.body: Write a wheels program that displays these objects. It must include the following classes: A Main class that extends wheels.users.Frame and includes a main method that launches the program. Make sure you name this class correctly and leave it in the default package so that my script can run your program. For each interactive object: At least one subclass of a wheels shape that reacts to mouse input. Another object that visibly responds to the mouse input. An interface that links the wheels shape(s) to the object(s) that they control. The wheels shape(s) must have an association with this interface, not the other object. The other object must implement this interface. You're free to include more classes in your project, but at a minimum you need a classes and interfaces that meet the requirements above. Group Work During one practice activity we worked on a component class for this project. If you worked with a group on that component, emailed the finished code to me by the end of class, and received a confirmation from me that all group members may use this code in their projects, then you can use that code in your project with proper credit to the rest of your from class group. Otherwise, all code in the project must be your own work.
15.title: Task 2: Program

16.body: Answer the following questions after completing your program. This reflection can be in the same document as your design writeup as long as long as it is clearly separated from your answers to the design questions. For each of your two interactive objects, create a UML diagram that includes the following classes and relationships (don't include any class members in the diagram): The interface used in the interaction The wheels shape subclass(es) responsible for detecting mouse input Any classes that implement your interface and the appropriate arrow for this relationship Any associations or composition relationships between the above classes and interfaces The superclass of each of the above classes and the appropriate arrow for this relationship Review your program and find a piece of code that was either challenging to write or that you think is an example of particularly good code (it's up to you what "good code" means, but you should be able to justify your opinion). Explain why you chose this code: why is it an example of good code or what was challenging about writing it? Include the code in your answer and note the line number(s) and file where it appears in your program. Review your program and find a piece of code that you think could be improved. What do you dislike or want to change about this code? If you were to spend more time on the project, how might you improve this code? To be clear, I'm not asking you how the program could be better. I don't want to know what feature you'd add or how you'd make it easier to use. I'm asking how part of the code could be better. This might mean shorter, easier to read, less repetitive, or something else that you value and think you could improve with additional time and/or programming knowledge. Include the code in your answer and note the line number(s) and file where it appears in your program.

18.body: Before submitting this assignment, make sure you understand and abide by the Academic Integrity policy in our syllabus. This is particularly important if you received any assistance, made use of an LLM, or used resources that were not provided in class. When uploading your code, package it in one of the following ways: If you're using Eclipse, then right-click on your project and choose "Export". Under "General", select "Archive File" and click "Next >". Ensure that all code for the project is checked, select a destination, and click "Finish". Note: the "Save in zip format" and "Create directory structure for files" options should be checked, and if you've linked to files outside the project you'll also need to check "Resolve and export linked resources". If all of your classes are in the default package, then you can directly attach each of the .java files to the Blackboard submission or zip them in a folder named "src". If some of your classes are not in the default package and you don't want to use Eclipse's export function, then you must place them in a folder named "src" with a directory structure matching the packages, zip that src folder, and upload the zipped folder with your submission. In order for this project to count as complete: upload all deliverables in a single Blackboard submission before the deadline (don't split it up between multiple submissions) your code must not contain any syntax errors the design writeup and reflection must be in PDF, ODT, DOC, DOCX, or plaintext files your work must demonstrate completion of each task in the assignment If you appear to have ignored portions of a task, did not submit the project as directed, or otherwise demonstrate negligence in your submission, then it will be marked "incomplete". If there are issues with your submission, but you appear to have made an honest effort to complete every task as directed, then your submission will be marked "revise" with comments requesting changes or additional work to complete the assignment.

24.body: Design a layout for your program. The layout must include at least two buttons or other interactive UI elements from the swing library, it must dedicate a large area to the drawing panel, and it must use at least two layout managers other than FlowLayout. You must show me the material listed below during class and submit it on Blackboard by 11:59 PM on Monday, April 14th . A sketch or mockup of your program An illustration of how layout managers will be used to create the program A sketch of mockup of what the drawing panel will display A description of how at least one swing UI element (JButton, JSlider, etc.) will affect the drawing panel A description of at least one mouse interaction that will affect the drawing panel The descriptions above must include a total of four interactions, divided as you wish between UI elements and mouse You may list additional mouse and UI element interactions separately, but you will not be required to implement them in Part 2 I may allow compromises when reviewing designs in class as long as they're not meant to trivialize the project (for example, using several regular jpanels instead of a single drawing panel). If you do not show me your design during class, then you will not receive feedback until after the deadline or be allowed to resubmit if the design is incomplete. Finally, note that I expect you to design your own program and draw/write the design yourself. Your design must not be based on a classmate's design, and you are not allowed to use ChatGPT or another AI/LLM to assist with the design.

5.body: To start, design a scene with at least three different types of objects. For example, your scene might be a bird flying through the sky with the sun and some clouds in the background. The bird, sun, and clouds would be our three types of object. Once you have an idea, think about how you could create these objects using wheels shapes (rectangles, ellipses, lines, and rounded rectangles). Our sun, for example, might be an ellipse with several lines radiating from it. I recommend drawing a quick sketch of the objects using those shapes. This will help you figure out how to create the objects using code. Once you've designed your scene, you need to design an object that functions as a component of another object in your scene. This component must appear multiple times in your code: either multiple times within the same object or in multiple types of object. Using our example, a single wing could be used as a component because our bird needs two of them. If we were going to include two different types of birds in our scene, then we might make a beak component and use it once in each bird class. In a separate document, answer the following questions about your design. This is your design writeup , and it must be submitted with the project. Summarize the entire scene. Describe three types of objects in your scene. What does each object represent, and how will you construct it out of wheels shapes? Your scene can include more types beyond these three, but the three you describe must meet the following requirements: The object is composed of at least three other objects (wheels shapes or component objects) The object is represented by its own class in your program The scene must include multiple instances of at least one object, so note an object that appears more than once in the scene Describe a component object that appears in the scene. What does this component object represent, how will you construct it out of wheels shapes, and what other object(s) will use it as a component? This component object must meet the following requirements: The component is composed of at least three wheels shapes The component is part of at least one type of object described in the previous question The component is either used multiple times in one object (for example, a bird with two instances of a wing component) or in different objects (for example, an eagle and an owl that each have a beak component) Finally, note that I expect you to design your own scene and write these descriptions yourself. Your scene should not be based on a classmate's scene or the example given in this section, and you are not allowed to use ChatGPT or another LLM to assist with this writeup.
5.title: Task 1: Design

6.body: Write a wheels program that displays your scene. It must include the following classes: A Main class that extends wheels.users.Frame and includes a main method that launches the program. Make sure you name this class correctly and leave it in the default package so that my script can run your program. One class for each type of object described in your design writeup. The classes should be named appropriately (upper camel case names that identify what type of object they represent). A class that defines the component described in your design writeup. Feel free to include more than the five required classes if you want to add more to your scene. Your three object types and your component must include the following constructors and methods: A setLocation method that moves the entire object to the given location A setColor method that changes at least one of the object's colors A default constructor that initializes all of the object's components and calls the above setter methods A parameterized constructor that accepts x, y coordinates for the object's location and at least one color; these parameters must be used to call the above setter methods Group Work During one practice activity we worked on a component class for this project. If you worked with a group on that component, emailed the finished code to me by 2/17, and received a confirmation from me that all group members may use this code in their projects, then you can use that code in your project with proper credit to the rest of your from class group. Otherwise, all code in the project must be your own work.
